If your data is currently in a “wide” format and you need to reshape it from a table where one column holds variable names, you’d usually use:
df = df.pivot(index=["Year", "Country"], columns="Variable", values="Value")

df = df.set_index(["Year", "Country"])

Use set_index if Year and Country are already separate columns.
Use pivot if one column contains variable names and another contains values.

``# Country as rows, variables as columns
df1 = df.pivot(index="Country", columns="Variable", values="Value")

# Year and Country both in rows (multi-index)
df2 = df.set_index(["Year", "Country"])

# Year as rows, countries as columns
df3 = df.pivot(index="Year", columns="Country", values="Value")``

In pandas, most “transformation” methods like pct_change operate either down each column (the default) or across each row. The axis parameter tells pandas which direction to compare:

• axis=0 (the default) means “compute change down each column” (i.e. compare with the previous row in the same column).
• axis=1 means “compute change across each row” (i.e. compare with the previous column in the same row).

